File:Â A photo of an electrical board. eNCA JOHANNESBURG - Electricity users in Johannesburg can breathe a sigh of relief. A proposed monthly electricity surcharge has been withdrawn.
The City of Johannesburg had planned a surcharge of R200 for prepaid residential electricity users and R400 for business users. READ: Govt announces eight bidders for emergency electricity generation The fee was supposed to kick-in in July. The City says it will instead go ahead with the planned tariff increase. A 14.59-percent increase across the board has been proposed. The new tariffs will come into effect on 1 July.